##Patients with major depressive disorder who have stopped taking their medication

Micro Signal Zhenshigushi1

Function description, every day a moving original true story.

"If only I could get pneumonia. " a siege can make a person with major depression have some terrible ideas. Under the threat of drug withdrawal, they began to help themselves and took active steps to help their more vulnerable patients. Between wanting to die and living well, these broken people rebuild their hearts again and again.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Year: 2020

Location: Fujian, Hubei, Beijing

Drug withdrawal

At 21:26, Sophomore kwang-zai struggles to wake up from her nightmare and is preparing to eat her first meal of the day. It wasn't the first time she'd turned her sleep upside down, she'd been living at night all winter vacation.

In December 2019, the 19-year-old went to a psychiatric clinic and was diagnosed with major depression. He began taking medication once a day as prescribed by his doctor. As a side effect of psychotropic drugs, she developed somatization symptoms such as lethargy, nausea and limb weakness.

"feel about to die, I am going to write a suicide note first. " This idea has been in the brain blast in the second round.

The side-effect of taking medicine is impatient, but Kony said, more painful is no medicine to eat: "medicine, is life. "

Once out, bomb boy lying in a hotel bed anxious, think of seems to forget to bring medicine. She didn't know what to do. She got up again and again to look for the medicine, but found nothing. She had to go back to bed. Dizziness, headaches, ringing in her ears, stinging in her eyes, and withdrawal symptoms kept her awake all night. Business failed, and she hurried back the next day.

Since then, kwang-zai no longer dare to stop without authorization, go anywhere with the drug. If she's traveling, she keeps a case and prescription in her suitcase, so she can go to the local doctor to get the medicine even if she runs out. The comfort of swallowing that little pill would give her a moment's peace of mind.

Back home in Fujian Province this Spring Festival, Kwang Tsai took 28 tablets of venlafaxine hydrochloride, one a day, enough to take at home during the Spring Festival. Originally thought that the hometown is not affected by the epidemic, if the drug ran out, on the local hospital to prescribe medicine. Results on January 30, the district where the bomber began to implement closed management. Kwang-chai later found out, February 7, the remaining drug only enough to eat for five days. She immediately thought of herself, vulnerable and in pain from the withdrawal, sinking into anxiety.

Do whatever it takes to get the medicine. I don't want to lose a second. Kwang-chai first checked the public number of the local mental health center, but found that the psychiatric clinic in the next few weeks are not scheduled. At this time, sandwiched between the medical records and a stack of prescription cards dropped on the ground, Kony picked up to find that is the visiting Doctor's card. Scanning the Qr Code, she entered the public number of an online clinic.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photo courtesy of interviewees | hong-zai buys medicine in online clinic

From the doctor online free clinic to check the prescription sheet, bomb waited for 4 hours. Then, boom boy waited another five days for a delivery. Until the home only a pill, bomb son would like to break it into two pieces to eat, the drug delivery courier finally arrived.

Under the epidemic situation, the city closed the village, the drug has become a group of patients with depression common face the reality of crisis.

At some point, the doctor gave him a 42-day dose. Kwang-zai got the medicine and breathed a sigh of relief. He clutched the package tightly. Prescription psychoactive drugs have strong side effects and can only be prescribed for up to two weeks at a time, and only in mental health centers or psychiatric departments of tertiary hospitals.

In 2017, when the WHO reported mental illness, the incidence of depression in China reached 4.2 percent. The latest figures show that the number of people suffering from depression in China has reached 90 million. However, there are only a few people like kwang-zai who rely on their own power to get the medicine.

"I've been off my medication for two days now, and my depression has gone from mild to severe. "

"I dare not go to the hospital to prescribe medicine, I am too weak. "

In the group, someone asked earnestly, "what if the people in the village knew I was looking for a drug for depression, and I couldn't get married? " The stigma made it harder to get the drugs, and it was easier for drug dealers to take advantage of the situation.

It is not uncommon for a drug dealer to pose as a patient in a post bar or group: "I can't finish my medicine, and 40g is cheap. " It is difficult for patients to tell whether the 40g is flour or expired medicine. Missed the regular treatment, unauthorized use of alternative medicine, there will be aggravated illness.

#Mutual Aid

Mutual Aid

After getting the "life-saving medicine" , kwang-zai failed to rely on the drug as expected to stabilize the good mood. The epidemic is increasingly serious, she holding the phone constantly refresh news, but the bad news is too much, has always been concerned about current events, she cried out abuse.

Despite the mood, kwang-jae persisted in browsing the messages: "It's not cool not to care. It takes real courage to care. "

That's a line from the movie transcendence. Kozak loved it. "It's a big deal for people like us to want to live, " says Kony. During the epidemic, she saw a number of AIDS patients in the online drug, accompanied by doubt, misunderstanding, abuse, Bomb sub-feel powerless. Perhaps because of the same illness, she was very conscious of these self-help: "The more people want to live, the more hope there is for us. " She had a little wish in her heart that she could help others like her trapped at home, who are at risk of going off their meds.

The rescue effort began at 4:23 a.m. on Feb. 8, when, one sleepless night, she rejoined a Weibo account to share her experience buying depression medication online during the outbreak. The next day, enthusiastic netizen sends the way that buys medicine on the net that collates oneself, Bomb Zai is verified hind again send a blog. Together with her friends, she enlisted the help of Weibo's big V to spread the word, and the post gradually gained popularity and attention.

Kwang-jae responded to hundreds of comments until his arm gave out. Over and over, she went out of her way to explain to her patients how to buy drugs online and how to operate the platform. Under the influence of the bomb, some can go out to buy medicine or because of the condition to improve the remaining drugs of patients, are willing to bear the postage, free drug, and drug-deficient epidemic area patients to share the difficulties.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
How to buy drugs on twitter

Accidents Happen fast. Two days later, her Weibo Account was maliciously reported, and the channel of communication between her and her patients was suddenly cut off. The pressure of the past few days and the injustice of this moment let Hong Zai gasp for breath, she put the mobile phone heavily back cover on the desktop, burst into tears.

After crying, she remembered a patient who had volunteered in Wuhan. Together, they have set up a wechat group to help patients with mental illness in the affected areas who can not be distributed by the online medical platform.

For a patient in Huanggang, Hubei Province, luck has come faster than expected. On February 11th, he contacted Wang through a micro blog post and a private message, and joined a mutual aid group. Huanggang was hit hard by the outbreak, and several of Huanggang's patients faced the same problem of drug withdrawal as a result of a complete block in their residential area and the failure to distribute medicines purchased online. "I am in Chongqing, I can buy medicine for you. " On the afternoon of February 16, a group friend who had suffered from depression offered to help Huanggang's friend buy medicine from another place and mail it. She says there are a lot of hospital pharmacies in her neighborhood, and all you have to do is provide a doctor's prescription to get the medicine you need.

There are more than 50 people in the support group, some patients through this way to get much-needed drugs, there are some patients with the same city uniform medicine, with the help of takeout errand boy to solve the immediate problem. Up to now, nearly 100 people have asked for her help, she is concerned about the needs of everyone every day, to confirm whether the delivery of drugs. In order to protect the privacy of patients, she asked as few questions as possible, and actively provided various ways to seek help.

However, there are still a lot of patients can not get the drug, which makes the bomb is very upset. Some of the inmates were quarantined in the countryside, where couriers and takeaways couldn't get in, and Kony watched them desperately seeking help. There are also drugs that are controlled by the state and are not sold online and need to be picked up in person at the hospital.

Despite his best efforts, he felt his power was too limited: "I am one of the victims of this epidemic, and I am just an ordinary person who has taken on social responsibilities for no reason. "

Fortunately, there are others who are looking out for people with depression in this effort. In a mutual help group in an epidemic area, kwang-zai saw a patient share his experience: "My doctor volunteered to ask if there is a shortage of medicine, has arranged for an assistant to send US medicine. "

Survival

Hidden in the drug crisis, is out of control out of self-harm, suicide thoughts. The whole group of depressed patients, under the influence of the information environment about the epidemic situation, rebuild their hearts again and again.

A news that a health care worker has been infected creates a strong "Survivor guilt" in depressed patients. "If only I could get pneumonia, " said one of the group, drawing some agreement.

For healthy people, the first response to an outbreak is to protect themselves and their families. But people with depression are naturally negative and world-weary, and the idea that the most 'appropriate' way to die from pneumonia might be to avoid the social pressure associated with suicide.

Even if not in the current special situation, every Spring Festival, when depressed patients back to the original family, contact with parents, elders, there will be huge mood swings.

Hubei Girl Yan Yu, a junior, has planned several deaths. She suffered from severe depression and it would have been awkward for her to go home for the New Year. Yan Yu's family is to reorganize the family, the mother and stepfather are very concerned about her, but in the end there is estrangement. Still have to go relatives, this more let Yan Yu feel pain.

On Weekdays, people with depression are accustomed to seek help from the first-and second-tier cities'mental health care system. After returning home, many small towns have not yet popularized psychological counseling services, and timely intervention will cause the condition to worsen. This year, the days of confinement in their homes have stretched out to infinity, and all sorts of negative emotions have been kindled in unpredictable ways and poured out at them.

After returning home in mid-january, Yan found his stepfather, a doctor, working overtime every day. Approaching the New Year's Eve, the city of Wuhan was closed, the epidemic intensified, stepfather even did not have time to go home. She and her mother were the only ones left, and everything was out of balance again. On February 5, the mother unconsciously said to Yan Yu: "It's been so long, why haven't you recovered? " All along, the mother was very understanding of Yan Yu's depression, everywhere to take care of her daughter's mood, but at the same time worried about her husband and daughter at the same time, it's too much for her.

In the evening, Yan Yu closed the door and stood in front of the window, once again want to jump. At this moment, her mother called her to eat, temporarily put out her thoughts of suicide, she did not have the heart to let her mother worry.

The next day, Yan Yu saw an online time donation campaign, in which a person named "Ren sick" donated nine hours, "Head of the Depression Research Institute, who has completed suicide interventions for hundreds of depressed patients, " the profile said. "she must understand me. " An idea flashed through Yan's mind.

Ren, whose real name is Ren Ke, is a 26-year-old entrepreneur. She was also a major depressive disorder patients, recovered in late 2018, opened a companion depression patients, "depression research institute" , Patients Call Her "director. Since the outbreak, Renke has been live streaming information about depression and psychology, and has only been able to spare some time for one-on-one psychological assistance.

To get the time of the donor, you need the help of a friend to like it. Yan Yu shared the link to her friend circle and QQ space, with a sentence attached: "I want to meet this director, please save the child, thank you. " Soon, more than 50 people clicked on it, leaving messages to cheer her up. With the help of friends, Yan Yu got a chance to chat.

Half an hour before the phone call, Yan Yu mood is very excited, frequently bring up the idea of suicide. In normal counseling, the counselor doesn't reveal his or her personal details, but Renko prefers it to be a conversation between friends.

Ren Can voluntarily bring up her own experience of depression, in her diagnosis, "9 years of suicidal behavior. ". "suddenly one day, the sun shines on me, I feel so comfortable, it turns out I have the ability to find beauty. " She wanted to tell Yan Yu, death is not a sweet solution.

At the other end of the line, Yan Yu took out two A4 sheets of white paper and took notes as he listened. Ren Ke praised her: "You can take the initiative to ask for help, is a very energetic girl, you must have a lot of things to do, just temporarily sick. "

Although many people with depression want to commit suicide, they are still preparing for a long-term life. Yan Yu told any can, she has a postgraduate examination plan, in good condition, she will sit down to review. Over the next few days, Yan Yu often interacted with ren when she was on air, reminding her to protect her voice.

Renke found that people with depression have a need to survive: they say they're too tired, they can't go on, they want to leave, and they do what they can to save themselves. For those struggling with depression, Renke said: "Not all suicide interventions need to be preachy and dissuasive. Sometimes they just need someone to teach them how to take a vacation. "

In Ren Ke's wechat account, there are hundreds of people suffering from depression. These days, there are still pictures of razor blades cutting through the arms. But out of the "don't want to live" voice, a girl suddenly said: "When this epidemic is over, I want to live. "

"Let's live long enough for something good to happen, " Ren wrote in her signature.

Empathy

On January 29,3,554 cases were confirmed in Hubei Province. As the epidemic deepens, so do the depressive patients.

On Feb. 10, Ren paused next to a comment on his facebook page. "Director, our whole family has been isolated, I can not sleep every night, what should I do? " The boy who left a message is a group called Li Hang, also in the epidemic area of Hubei.

See"family isolation"a few words, Ren can be very worried about Li hang's physical and psychological state, immediately replied: Let's talk about it.

The voice over the phone is calm, but ren can still feel the other side's anxiety. At the beginning, the boy named Li Hong poured out his situation quickly. Before the Spring Festival, he, his parents and grandparents were transferred to the quarantine area because of suspected infection, one of them lived in an empty room. In addition to the regular delivery of rice and Chinese Medicine, hospital medical resources are scarce, the family can not further diagnosis and treatment.

"My grandfather is almost 90 years old, and he fainted on the first day of isolation, but there is nothing I can do, " said Li Hang, 24, who blames himself for not protecting his family ahead of time. Now living in the same building but unable to meet, "I'm afraid they won't make it. " He often can't even say a word of concern after opening the family group.

Li Hang Shuts himself up, repeatedly self-torture, a public health event caused by the stress response, is making his heart constantly collapsed. Not a voice told him it wasn't his fault.

"Even if temporarily unable to meet, tell your family your concerns, for them is also a support. " Ren Can persuade Li Hang. She knows that many men are reluctant to express "unhappiness" and helplessness under the pressure of social environment, so she advised him: "If you want to cry, the Group of patients are waiting for you to talk. "

"Actually, the child you should take care of most is yourself, " Ren Ke said.

Until Ren can say this sentence, Li hang just willing to open the bottom of the heart vulnerable part, talk about their state. He has not eaten or slept more than three hours a day since his isolation began more than ten days ago. As soon as you lie down, your mind starts playing a loop of something you've been struggling to let go of for a long time.

It was freshman year, and counselors were giving freshman psych tests. After everyone finished, they forgot about it, until one afternoon, a counselor called out a girl's name in the grade QQ group, "please come to the psychological consulting room at once. " Later, the students began to discuss the matter, girls face discrimination and hostility throughout the university.

"Why didn't I do something then? " Li Hang Asks Ren Ke. Like the epidemic that followed, Li's suffering was magnified by his sensitivity and powerlessness.

Ren Can try to distract him and help find something he can do, "You see, now you have all the time in the world, to study psychology that interests you. You want to help more people, but you can't be beaten down by depression before a little pneumonia has knocked you down. " Li, on the verge of collapse, was given a floating board.

"people with depression are particularly empathetic, " Renko found. At the beginning of the New Year, a number of non-profit organizations and Internet companies have launched psychological assistance online, opening a 24-hour consultation hotline for the public. But people with severe depression are reluctant to make the call. A common mindset is: "The people in the affected areas may be in more pain than I am, and I can't use public resources just because of a little psychological problem. "

Around February 1, the outbreak of information increased exponentially, the first response of patients with depression is self-dedication.

"You are the 969966 th volunteer to register on this platform, " a patient shared a Chinese organ donation registration card in the group. Those who see the card can scan the Qr code on it to register as a donor, donating bodies, organs and corneas. Like the relay, a dozen consecutive patients scan code registration, Ren can also join them.

Volunteer Registration Card in patient group

Some patients think they enjoy social resources, but they can't help others like medical staff, and they are overly immersed in guilt. They would then spontaneously donate organs, describing the event as a "coupon purchase. ". Thinking that you can't do anything right now, but if you leave one day, your body can save people, your body can become a general teacher, make contributions to medicine, and your friends can get some psychological compensation.

"We're only a few numbers apart, and I'll probably be in the third bed next to you, " said another. Patients often like this joke, Ren can feel that they are cute and heartrending.

* Yan Yu and Li hang were given pseudonyms

By Cheng Kun and Li Yi
